GameLoop is the per-turn match stepper: begin binds a GameState and opens the runtime trace, and an external driver calls step once per turn until it returns false. Each step advances m_current_turn, then runs cities before units so production and growth see last turn’s unit censuses. City work goes through CityTurnHandler (yields, growth, production finish, this-turn city and population tallies) and a temporary settler-build nudge driven by SettlerTurnHandler::need_settler. After the city pass, this-turn city and population counts copy into the last-turn fields, this-turn counters reset, and the unit tallies (settlers, workers, defensive) zero so the unit pass can recount them cleanly.

The unit pass scans the unit pool for live entries, then dispatches WorkerTurnHandler and DefensiveUnitTurnHandler for counting (and later AI), and SettlerTurnHandler only for LAND_SETTLER units after a movement-point refill. SettlerTurnHandler still owns mission slots, site refresh, pathing, and founding; workers and defensive handlers are intentionally thin. Empty unit slots are ordinary skips in the scan; broken invariants such as a null city inside the city count use GAME_EXPECT instead of defensive returns. Turn-limit exhaustion is also ordinary control flow: step returns false when m_current_turn has reached m_turn_limit so the driver can stop.

What remains thin or temporary: settler production still force-feeds production for testing, worker and defensive AI do little beyond census, and other unit roles (scouts, attack, naval) have no handlers yet. PlayerState’s last-turn versus this-turn counters exist so cities→units ordering can keep a stable previous census without flipping the phase order. Extending the loop means adding more *TurnHandler call sites in the unit scan and growing those handlers, not inventing a second stepper beside GameLoop.
